Japan, China, India, Thailand, Indonesia: Asian Bonds and Currency Preview

-- B y   V .   R a m a k r i s h n a n
-- 
2011-05-31T22:16:32Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-31/japan-china-india-thailand-indonesia-asian-bonds-and-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in  Asia ’s bonds and currencies
today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the previous
trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan : Chief Cabinet Secretary Yukio Edano will hold media
briefings at 11 a.m. and 4 p.m. in  Tokyo . The  Bank of Japan  will
hold a two-day international conference in Tokyo starting at 9
a.m. local time. Governor Masaaki Shirakawa will deliver a
speech at the conference.  The Ministry of Finance is scheduled to sell 2.2 trillion
yen ($27 billion) of 10-year debt.  The yield on the 1.1 percent government bond due March 2021
was 1.15 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 81.47 per dollar at 7:08 a.m. in Tokyo.  China : A manufacturing purchasing managers index fell to
51.6 in May from 52.9 in April, according to the median estimate
in a Bloomberg News survey of economists before the data is
published today.  The government will sell 30 billion yuan ($4.6 billion) of
three-year bonds today.  The yield on the 3.83 percent bond due March 2021 was 3.83
percent, according to Chinabond, the nation’s biggest debt-
clearing house. The yuan was at 6.4791.  India : The commerce ministry will publish trade data for
April today. Exports increased 43.9 percent in March from a year
earlier and imports rose 17.3 percent.  The  finance ministry  will sell 80 billion rupees of 91-day
bills ($1.8 billion) and 30 billion rupees of 364-day bills
today.  The yield on the 7.80 percent bond due April 2021 was 8.40
percent. The rupee was at 45.0400.  South Korea : A government report today will show the
consumer price index rose 4.2 percent in May from a year earlier,
according to a Bloomberg News survey.  South Korea’s trade surplus was $4.5 billion in May,
compared with $5.8 billion in April, according to the median
estimate in a Bloomberg News survey of economists before the
Ministry of Knowledge Economy publishes the data today.  The yield on South Korea’s 3 percent bond due December 2013
was 3.59 percent. The won was at 1,079.15 per dollar.  Indonesia: A government report today will show year-on-year
inflation was 5.94 percent in May, compared with 6.16 percent in
April, according to the median estimate of economists surveyed
by Bloomberg News.  The  trade surplus  was $1.4 billion in April, compared with
$1.8 billion in March, according to another Bloomberg survey
before data due today.  The yield on the 8.25 percent bond due July 2021 was 7.39
percent. The rupiah was at 8,538.  Thailand: The central bank will boost its benchmark
interest rate to 3 percent from 2.75 percent, according to all
16 economists surveyed by Bloomberg.  Consumer prices rose 4.3 percent in May from a year earlier,
the most since September 2008, a government report will say
today, according to a separate poll.  The yield on the 3.125 percent debt due December 2015 was
3.46 percent. The baht was at 30.31 per dollar.  Malaysia: The central bank will sell a combined 3 billion
ringgit ($997 million) of 54- and 168-day notes today. It will
also sell 1.5 billion ringgit of 84-day Islamic notes.  The yield on the benchmark 4.16 percent note due July 2021
was at 4.01 percent. The ringgit was at 3.0100.  To contact the reporter on this story:
